<br>
As a raidleader, the last thing I want to do upon finally finding a mob up to kill is to waste further time alt+entering out of EQ and posting our intention to kill it on some board noone reads.<br>
<br>
I may browse the battlefield occasionally to see if there is an open raid on UK time organised by someone other than me or Pat that I might want to attend, but other than that, I pay nil attention to it.<br>
<br>
Battlefield is a great tool for organising open raids.  But I learnt myself that its never good to have a fixed raid target.  Always have some backup targets.<br>
<br>
Battlefield is not a system that allows you to reserve mobs.  I'm sorry but how often have you reserved a table somewhere and skanked on the reservation, ditto for taxis in town late at night when you get another one first. <br>
<br>
FCFS is perfectly fair.  If you get your raid to the zone before another raidforce, they should give you a fair shot at killing the mob.  In reality, if someone else was already prepping to kill a mob in a zone, I would take my raidforce somewhere else, its not worth hanging about to see if they fail, it wastes valuable raidtime, may as well go find something else up.<br>
<br>
So if your Vox raid gets to the evening and Vox isn't up, just raid Ixiblat or Chardok Royals or PoHate instead.  <br>
